# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ground-and-neutral
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:ground-and-neutral/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] These appliances have no protective-earth connection and feature only a single level of insulation between live parts and exposed metalwork.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] If permitted at all, Class 0 items are intended for use in dry areas only.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] A single fault could cause an electric shock or other dangerous occurrence, without triggering the automatic operation of any fuse or circuit breaker.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Sales of such items have been prohibited in much of the world for safety reasons, for example in the UK by Section 8 of The Low Voltage Electrical Equipment (Safety) Regulations 1989 and New Zealand by the Electricity Act.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] A typical example of a Class 0 appliance is the old style of Christmas fairy lights.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] However, equipment of this class is common in some 120 V countries, and in much of the 230 V developing world, whether permitted officially or not.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] These appliances do not have their chassis connected to electrical earth.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] In many countries the plug of a Class 0 equipment is such that it cannot be inserted to grounded outlet like Schuko.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] The failure of such an equipment in a location where there are grounded equipment can cause fatal shock if one touches both.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Any Class 1 equipment will act like a Class 0 equipment when connected to an ungrounded outlet.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Appliance Class I is not only based on the basic insulation, but the casing and other conductive parts are also connected with a low-resistant earth conductor.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Hence, these appliances must have their chassis connected to electrical earth (US: ground) by a separate earth conductor (coloured green/yellow in most countries, green in India, US, Canada and Japan).
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] The earth connection is achieved with a three-conductor mains cable, typically ending with three-prong AC connector which plugs into a corresponding AC outlet.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Plugs are designed such that the connection to the protective earth conductor should be the first connection when plugged in.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] It should also be the last to be broken when the plug is removed.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] A fault in the appliance which causes a live conductor to contact the casing will cause a current to flow in the earth conductor.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] If large enough, this current will trip an over-current device (fuse or circuit breaker) and disconnect the supply.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] The disconnection time has to be fast enough not to allow fibrillation to start if a person is in contact with the casing at the time.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] This time and the current rating in turn sets a maximum earth resistance permissible.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Electrical installations where the chassis is connected to earth with a separate terminal, instead of via the mains cable.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] In effect this provides the same automatic disconnection as Class I, for equipment that otherwise would be Class 0.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] A Class II or **double insulated** electrical appliance uses reinforced protective insulation in addition to basic insulation.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Hence, it has been designed in such a way that it does not require a safety connection to electrical earth (ground).
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] The basic requirement is that no single failure can result in dangerous voltage becoming exposed so that it might cause an electric shock and that this is achieved without relying on an earthed metal casing.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] This is usually achieved at least in part by having at least two layers of insulating material between live parts and the user, or by using reinforced insulation.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] In Europe, a double insulated appliance must be labelled *Class II* or *double insulated* or bear the double insulation symbol: ⧈ (a square inside another square).
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] As such, the appliance should not be connected to an earth conductor because the high-impedance casing will cause only low-fault currents that are unable to trigger the fusible cut-out.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Insulated AC/DC power supplies (such as cell-phone chargers) are typically designated as Class II, meaning that the DC output wires are galvanically isolated from the AC input.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Caveat: The designation "Class II" should not be confused with the designation "Class 2", as the latter is unrelated to insulation (it originates from standard UL 1310, setting limits on maximum output voltage/current/power).
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] These devices have a Functional Earth "FE".
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] This differs from a protective earth ground in that it does not offer shock protection from a hazardous voltage.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] However, it does help to mitigate electromagnetic noise or EMI.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] This is often important in audio and medical design.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Since they also include double insulation, users will not come into contact with any live parts.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] A Class III appliance is designed to be supplied from a separated extra-low voltage (SELV) power source.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] The voltage from a SELV supply is low enough such that under normal conditions a person can safely come into contact with an energized conductor without risk of electrical shock.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] The additional safety features required by Class I and Class II appliances are therefore not required.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Specifically, Class III appliances are designed without an earth conductor and should not be connected to the earth grounding of the SELV power source.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] For medical devices, compliance with Class III is *not* considered sufficient protection, and furthermore, stringent regulations apply to such equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] The Class III label does not guarantee a device's safety in any aspect other than electrical shock.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Even at low voltages, abusive or unintended use (such as disassembly or incorrect installation) may still yield dangerous outcomes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] Although there should be no risk of receiving an electrical shock from Class III appliances, other electrical hazards (such as overheating and fire) must still be considered.
[src:ground-and-neutral/appliance-classes] For instance, a laptop or mobile phone might qualify as a Class III appliance if it is charged via an external SELV adapter, even though the onboard battery could pose a fire risk.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] A **clothes dryer** (**tumble dryer**, **drying machine**,**drying device**, or simply **dryer**) is a powered household appliance that is used to remove moisture from a load of clothing, bedding and other textiles, usually after they are washed in the washing machine.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Many dryers consist of a rotating drum called a "tumbler" through which heated air is circulated to evaporate moisture while the tumbler is rotated to maintain air space between the articles.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Using such a machine may cause clothes to shrink or become less soft (by loss of short soft fibers).
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] A simpler non-rotating machine called a "drying cabinet" may be used for delicate fabrics and other items not suitable for a tumble dryer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Other machines include steam to de-shrink clothes and eliminate the need for ironing.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Tumble dryers continuously draw in air from their surroundings and heat it before passing it through the tumbler.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The resulting hot, humid air is usually vented outside to make room for more air to continue the drying process.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Often the washer and dryer functions will have a different capacity, with the dryer usually having a lower capacity than the washer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Tumble dryers can also be top loading, with the drum loaded from the top of the machine and the drum's end supports in the left and right sides, instead of the more conventional front and rear.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] They can be as narrow as 40 centimetres (16 in) in width, and may include detachable stationary racks for drying items like plush toys and footwear.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] These centrifuge machines simply spin their drums much faster than a typical washer could, in order to extract additional water from the load.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] They may remove more water in two minutes than a heated tumble dryer can in twenty, thus saving significant amounts of time and energy.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Although spinning alone will not completely dry clothing, this additional step saves a worthwhile amount of time and energy for large laundry operations such as those of hospitals.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Just as in a tumble dryer, condenser or condensation dryers pass heated air through the load.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] However, instead of exhausting this air, the dryer uses a heat exchanger to cool the air and condense the water vapor into either a drain pipe or a collection tank.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The drier air is run through the loop again.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The heat exchanger typically uses ambient air as its coolant, therefore the heat produced by the dryer will go into the immediate surroundings instead of the outside, increasing the room temperature.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] In some designs, cold water is used in the heat exchanger, eliminating this heating, but requiring increased water usage.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] In terms of energy use, condenser dryers typically require around 2 kilowatt hours (kW⋅h) of energy per average load.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Because the heat exchange process simply cools the internal air using ambient air (or cold water in some cases), it will not dry the air in the internal loop to as low a level of humidity as typical fresh, ambient air.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] As a consequence of the increased humidity of the air used to dry the load, this type of dryer requires somewhat more time than a tumble dryer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Condenser dryers are a particularly attractive option where long, intricate ducting would be required to vent the dryer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] A closed-cycle heat pump clothes dryer uses a heat pump to dehumidify the processing air.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Such dryers typically use under half the energy per load of a condenser dryer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Whereas condensation dryers use a passive heat exchanger cooled by ambient air, these dryers use a heat pump.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The hot, humid air from the tumbler is passed through a heat pump where the cold side condenses the water vapor into either a drain pipe or a collection tank and the hot side reheats the air afterward for re-use.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] In this way not only does the dryer avoid the need for ducting, but it also conserves much of its heat within the dryer instead of exhausting it into the surroundings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Heat pump dryers can, therefore, use up to 50% less energy required by either condensation or conventional electric dryers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Heat pump dryers use about 1 kW⋅h of energy to dry an average load instead of 2 kW⋅h for a condenser dryer, or from 3 to 9 kW⋅h, for a conventional electric dryer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Domestic heat pump dryers are designed to work in typical ambient temperatures from 5 to 30 °C (41 to 86 °F).
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Below 5 °C (41 °F), drying times significantly increase.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] As with condensation dryers, the heat exchanger will not dry the internal air to as low a level of humidity as the typical ambient air.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] A new type of dryer in development, these machines are a more advanced version of heat pump dryers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Instead of using hot air to dry the clothing, mechanical steam compression dryers use water recovered from the clothing in the form of steam.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] First, the tumbler and its contents are heated to 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The wet steam that results purges the system of air and is the only remaining atmosphere in the tumbler.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] As wet steam exits the tumbler, it is mechanically compressed (hence the name) to extract water vapor and transfer the heat of vaporization to the remaining gaseous steam.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] This pressurized, gaseous steam is then allowed to expand, and is superheated before being injected back into the tumbler where its heat causes more water to vaporize from the clothing, creating more wet steam and restarting the cycle.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Like heat pump dryers, mechanical steam compression dryers recycle much of the heat used to dry the clothes, and they operate in a very similar range of efficiency as heat pump dryers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Both types can be over twice as efficient as conventional tumble dryers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The considerably higher temperatures used in mechanical steam compression dryers result in drying times on the order of half as long as those of heat pump dryers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Marketed by some manufacturers as a "static clothes drying technique", convectant dryers simply consist of a heating unit at the bottom, a vertical chamber, and a vent at top.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The unit heats air at the bottom, reducing its relative humidity, and the natural tendency of hot air to rise brings this low-humidity air into contact with the clothes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] This design is slower than conventional tumble dryers, but relatively energy-efficient if well-implemented.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] It works particularly well in cold and humid environments, where it dries clothes substantially faster than line-drying.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] In hot and dry weather, the performance delta over line-drying is negligible.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Given that this is a relatively simple and cheap technique to materialize, most consumer products showcase the added benefit of portability and/or modularity.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Newer designs implement a fan heater at the bottom to pump hot air into the vertical drying rack chamber.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Temperatures in excess of 60 °C (140 °F) can be reached inside these "hot air balloons," yet lint, static cling, and shrinkage are minimal.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Upfront cost is significantly lower than tumble, condenser and heat pump designs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] If used in combination with washing machines featuring fast spin cycles (800+ rpm) or spin dryers, the cost-effectiveness of this technique has the potential to render tumble dryer-like designs obsolete in single-person and small family households.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] One disadvantage is that the moisture from the clothes is released into the immediate surroundings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Proper ventilation or a complementary dehumidifier is recommended for indoor use.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] It also cannot compete with the tumble dryer's capacity to dry multiple loads of wet clothing in a single day.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The solar dryer is a box-shaped stationary construction which encloses a second compartment where the clothes are held.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] It uses the sun's heat without direct sunlight reaching the clothes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Alternatively, a solar heating box may be used to heat air that is driven through a conventional tumbler dryer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Japanese manufacturers have developed highly efficient clothes dryers that use microwave radiation to dry the clothes (though a vast majority of Japanese air dry their laundry).
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Most of the drying is done using microwaves to evaporate the water, but the final drying is done by convection heating, to avoid problems of arcing with metal pieces in the laundry.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] There are a number of advantages: shorter drying times (25% less), energy savings (17–25% less), and lower drying temperatures.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Some analysts think that the arcing and fabric damage is a factor preventing microwave dryers from being developed for the US market.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Ultrasonic dryers use high-frequency signals to drive piezoelectric actuators in order to mechanically shake the clothes, releasing water in the form of a mist which is then removed from the drum.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] They have the potential to significantly cut energy consumption while needing only one-third of the time needed by a conventional electric dryer for a given load.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] They also do not have the same issues related with lint in most other types of dryers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Some manufacturers, like LG Electronics and Whirlpool, have introduced hybrid dryers, that offer the user the option of using either a heat pump or a traditional electric heating element for drying the user's clothes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Hybrid dryers can also use a heat pump and a heating element at the same time to dry clothes faster.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] This type of dryer, commonly found in Japan, is installed in the bathroom.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] A unit combining a blower and an exhaust fan is built into the ceiling; it blows warm air onto damp clothes while simultaneously extracting excess moisture from the room.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Its power consumption is lower than that of a tumble dryer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Additionally, since the warm air isn’t extremely hot, it causes minimal damage to clothing.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] In Japan, bathrooms and toilets are often located in separate rooms.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] As a result, even in larger homes, bathrooms tend to be compact.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] This allows the unit to circulate warm air throughout the entire bathroom and dry clothes effectively, even with its low power consumption.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Clothes dryers can cause static cling through the triboelectric effect.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] This can be a minor nuisance and is often a symptom of over-drying textiles to below their equilibrium moisture level, particularly when using synthetic materials.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Fabric conditioning products such as dryer sheets are marketed to dissipate this static charge, depositing surfactants onto the fabric load by mechanical abrasion during tumbling.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Modern dryers often have improved temperature and humidity sensors and electronic controls which aim to stop the drying cycle once textiles are sufficiently dry, avoiding over-drying and the static charge and energy wastage this causes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Drying at a minimum of 60 °C (140 °F) heat for thirty minutes kills many parasites including house dust mites, bed bugs, and scabies mites and their eggs; a bit more than ten minutes kills ticks.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Simply washing drowns dust mites, and exposure to direct sunlight for three hours kills their eggs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Moisture and lint are byproducts of the tumble drying process and are pulled from the drum by a fan motor and then pushed through the remaining exhaust conduit to the exterior termination fitting.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Typical exhaust conduit comprises flex transition hose found immediately behind the dryer, the 4-inch (100 mm) rigid galvanized pipe and elbow fittings found within the wall framing, and the vent duct hood found outside the house.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] A clean, unobstructed dryer vent improves both the efficiency and safety of the dryer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] As the dryer duct pipe becomes partially obstructed and filled with lint, drying time markedly increases and causes the dryer to waste energy.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] A blocked vent increases the internal temperature and may result in a fire.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Clothes dryers are one of the more costly home appliances to operate.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Several factors can contribute to or accelerate rapid lint build-up.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] These include long or restrictive ducts, bird or rodent nests in the termination, crushed or kinked flex transition hose, terminations with screen-like features, and condensation within the duct due to un-insulated ducts traveling through cold spaces such as a crawl space or attic.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] If plastic flaps are at the outside end of the duct, one may be able to flex, bend, and temporarily remove the plastic flaps, clean the inside surface of the flaps, clean the last foot or so of the duct, and reattach the plastic flaps.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The plastic flaps keep insects, birds, and snakes out of the dryer vent pipe.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] During cold weather, the warm wet air condenses on the plastic flaps, and minor trace amounts of lint sticks to the wet inside part of the plastic flaps at the outside of the building.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Ventless dryers include multi-stage lint filtration systems and some even include automatic evaporator and condenser cleaning functions that can run even while the dryer is running.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The evaporator and condenser are usually cleaned with running water.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] These systems are necessary, in order to prevent lint from building up inside the dryer and evaporator and condenser coils.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Aftermarket add-on lint and moisture traps can be attached to the dryer duct pipe, on machines originally manufactured as outside-venting, to facilitate installation where an outside vent is not available.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Increased humidity at the location of installation is a drawback to this method.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Dryers expose flammable materials to heat.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Underwriters Laboratories recommends cleaning the lint filter after every cycle for safety and energy efficiency, provision of adequate ventilation, and cleaning of the duct at regular intervals.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] UL also recommends that dryers not be used for glass fiber, rubber, foam or plastic items, or any item that has had a flammable substance spilled on it.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] In the United States, an estimate from the US Fire Administration in a 2012 report estimated that from 2008 to 2010, fire departments responded to an estimated 2,900 clothes dryer fires in residential buildings each year across the nation.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] These fires resulted in an annual average loss of 5 deaths, 100 injuries, and $35 million in property loss.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] To address the problem of clothes dryer fires, a fire suppression system can be used with sensors to detect the change in temperature when a blaze starts in a dryer drum.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] These sensors then activate a water vapor mechanism to put out the fire.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The environmental impact of clothes dryers is especially severe in the US and Canada, where over 80% of all homes have a clothes dryer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Clothes dryers are second only to refrigerators and freezers as the largest residential electrical energy consumers in America.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] In the European Union, the EU energy labeling system is applied to dryers; dryers are classified with a label from A+++ (best) to G (worst) according to the amount of energy used per kilogram of clothes (kW⋅h/kg).
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Sensor dryers can automatically sense that clothes are dry and switch off.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] This means over-drying is not as frequent.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Most of the European market sells sensor dryers now, and they are normally available in condenser and vented dryers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] A hand-cranked clothes dryer was created in 1800 by M.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] The first patented automatic clothes dryer was invented by African American inventor George T.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Sampson in 1892, utilizing a rack over a stove to safely dry clothes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Patent #476,416) that used a frame to hold clothes over a stove, which was safer and more efficient than previous methods.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Altorfer invented and patented an electric clothes dryer in 1937.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Ross Moore, an inventor from North Dakota, developed designs for automatic clothes dryers and published his design for an electrically operated dryer in 1938.
[src:ground-and-neutral/clothes-dryer] Industrial designer Brooks Stevens developed an electric dryer with a glass window in the early 1940s.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] A **cooktop** (American and Canadian English), **hob** (British English), or **stovetop** (general) is a device commonly used for cooking that is typically found in kitchens and used to apply heat to the base of pans or pots.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Cooktops are often found integrated with an oven into a kitchen stove but may also be standalone devices.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Cooktops are most often powered by gas or electricity, although oil or other fuels are sometimes used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] A cooktop may also be called a **stove** or **range**, though in more formal usage these refer collectively to the stovetop and the furnace or appliance beneath.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Gas cooktops consist of one or more gas burners with arrangements to control the rate of flow.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] They often have integral lighters or (in older models) pilot lights, and may have safety interlocks designed to reduce the risk of hazardous gas leaks.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Gas cooking has been associated with negative health effects, such as reduced pulmonary function and a higher rate of respiratory symptoms in children.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] An **electric coil cooktop** uses electric elements that directly heat pots placed on them.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] They are inexpensive to buy and maintain, but are considered more difficult to clean than smooth-top or plate models.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] An **electric plate cooktop** is similar to a coil cooktop but uses plate-like base supports as opposed to coil supports.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] A **ceramic radiation heating cooktop** or radiant cooktop has a surface made of low-expansion thermal glass-ceramic that is transparent to infrared.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] This surface houses radiant or halogen heaters below it.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] These heaters primarily radiate heat as infrared light, hence the term radiant.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] The advantage of this arrangement is that the heat can be quickly controlled.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] These cooktops are often simply called **ceramic cooktop** or **ceramic-glass cooktop**, because they were the first type of cooktop to use glass-ceramic—however, other types of cooktops also use glass-ceramic surfaces, notably induction cooktops.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] An **induction cooktop** involves the electrical heating of a cooking vessel by magnetic induction instead of by radiation or thermal conduction from an electrical heating element or from a flame.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Because inductive heating directly heats the vessel, very rapid increases in temperature can be achieved and changes in heat settings are fast, similar to gas.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] In an induction cooktop ("induction hob" or "induction stove"), a coil of copper wire is placed under the cooking pot, and an alternating electric current is passed through it.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] The resulting oscillating magnetic field induces a magnetic flux that repeatedly magnetises the pot, treating it like the lossy magnetic core of a transformer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] This produces large eddy currents in the pot, which, because of the resistance of the pot, heat it.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] For nearly all models of induction cooktops, a cooking vessel must be made of, or contain, a ferromagnetic metal such as cast iron or some stainless steels.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] However, copper, glass, non-magnetic stainless steels, and aluminum vessels can be used if placed on a ferromagnetic disk that functions as a conventional hotplate.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Induction cooking is quite efficient, which means it puts less waste heat into the kitchen, can be quickly turned off, and has safety advantages compared to gas stoves.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Cooktops are also usually easy to clean, because the cooktop itself does not get very hot.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] If the induction coil is of lesser diameter than the cooking pot, and the pot has low thermal conductivity, use of high power can potentially warp the pot due to non-uniform heating.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] 6" coils are common in low-end portable units, which is smaller than most pots and pans.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Electric plasma cooktops are designed to be similar to gas stoves, but without using liquid or gaseous fuel.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] The electrodes and electric arc are exposed to air, similarly to a gas flame in a gas burner.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] The electrodes are arranged in pairs and several pairs make up a burner.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] The high temperature of the plasma is then used to heat cookware and can also ignite flammable materials, similarly to a gas flame and thus these cooktops are also known as electric flame cooktops, and can be used with cookware that is not made of metal and thus incompatible with induction cooktops.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] These cooktops are different from those with "virtual flames" which are LED lights placed around an induction cooktop and do not generate heat themselves, since the heat is generated using induction.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Cooktops often have a kitchen hood installed overhead to expel or filter smoke, fumes and undesirable odors that result from cooking.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] However, when installation of an updraft ventilation system is undesirable or impossible (for example in an open kitchen design), a cooktop with an integrated *downdraft* ventilation system can be used instead.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Such systems draw cooking fumes downwards rather than upwards, eliminating the need of an overhead installation.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] They are, however, less effective than overhead systems, and may not be able to extract fumes emanating from taller pots.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Cooktops are virtually ubiquitous in kitchens.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] They may be built into a stove along with an oven.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Alternatively, cooktops are often installed independently in work surfaces.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] A hot plate or hotplate is a portable self-contained tabletop small appliance cooktop with one, two or more electric heating elements, or gas burners.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] A hot plate can be used as a standalone appliance, but is often used as a substitute for one of the burners from an oven range or a kitchen stove.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Hot plates are often used for food preparation, generally in locations where a full kitchen stove would not be convenient or practical.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] A hot plate can have a flat or round surface.
[src:ground-and-neutral/cook-top] Hot plates can be used for traveling or in areas without electricity.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper has been used in electrical wiring since the invention of the electromagnet and the telegraph in the 1820s.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The invention of the telephone in 1876 created further demand for copper wire as an electrical conductor.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper is the electrical conductor in many categories of electrical wiring.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper wire is used in power generation, power transmission, electric power distribution, telecommunications, electronics circuitry, and countless types of electrical equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper and its alloys are also used to make electrical contacts.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Electrical wiring in buildings is the most important market for the copper industry.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Roughly half of all copper mined is used to manufacture electrical wire and cable conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Electrical conductivity is a measure of how well a material transports an electric charge.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This is an essential property in electrical wiring systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper has the highest electrical conductivity rating of all non-precious metals: the electrical resistivity of copper = 16.78 nΩ•m at 20 °C.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The theory of metals in their solid state helps to explain the unusually high electrical conductivity of copper.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] In a copper atom, the outermost 4s energy zone, or conduction band, is only half filled, so many electrons are able to carry electric current.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] When an electric field is applied to a copper wire, the conduction of electrons accelerates towards the electropositive end, thereby creating a current.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] These electrons encounter resistance to their passage by colliding with impurity atoms, vacancies, lattice ions, and imperfections.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The average distance travelled between collisions, defined as the mean free path, is inversely proportional to the resistivity of the metal.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] What is unique about copper is its long mean free path (approximately 100 atomic spacings at room temperature).
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This mean free path increases rapidly as copper is chilled.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Because of its superior conductivity, annealed copper became the international standard to which all other electrical conductors are compared.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] In 1913, the International Electrotechnical Commission defined the conductivity of commercially pure copper in its International Annealed Copper Standard, as 100% IACS = 58.0 MS/m at 20 °C, decreasing by 0.393%/°C.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Because commercial purity has improved over the last century, copper conductors used in building wire often slightly exceed the 100% IACS standard.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The main grade of copper used for electrical applications is electrolytic-tough pitch (ETP) copper (CW004A or ASTM designation C11040).
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This copper is at least 99.90% pure and has an electrical conductivity of at least 101% IACS.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] ETP copper contains a small percentage of oxygen (0.02 to 0.04%).
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] If high conductivity copper needs to be welded or brazed or used in a reducing atmosphere, then specially-pure oxygen-free copper (CW008A or ASTM designation C10100) may be used; it is about 1% more conductive (i.e., achieves a minimum of 101% IACS).
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Several electrically conductive metals are less dense than copper, but require larger cross sections to carry the same current and may not be usable when limited space is a major requirement.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Aluminium has 61% of the conductivity of copper.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The cross sectional area of an aluminium conductor must be 56% larger than copper for the same current carrying capability.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The need to increase the thickness of aluminium wire restricts its use in many applications, such as in small motors and automobiles.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] However, in some applications such as aerial electric power transmission cables, aluminium predominates, and copper is rarely used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Silver, a precious metal, is the only metal with a higher electrical conductivity than copper.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The electrical conductivity of silver is 106% of that of annealed copper on the IACS scale, and the electrical resistivity of silver = 15.9 nΩ•m at 20 °C.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The high cost of silver combined with its low tensile strength limits its use to special applications, such as joint plating and sliding contact surfaces, and plating for the conductors in high-quality coaxial cables used at frequencies above 30 MHz.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Tensile strength measures the force required to pull an object such as rope, wire, or a structural beam to the point where it breaks.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The tensile strength of a material is the maximum amount of tensile stress it can take before breaking.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper's higher tensile strength (200–250 N/mm2 annealed) compared to aluminium (100 N/mm2 for typical conductor alloys) is another reason why copper is used extensively in the building industry.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper's high strength resists stretching, neck-down, creep, nicks and breaks, and thereby also prevents failures and service interruptions.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper is much heavier than aluminum for conductors of equal current carrying capacity, so the high tensile strength is offset by its increased weight.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Ductility is a material's ability to deform under tensile stress.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This is often characterized by the material's ability to be stretched into a wire.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Ductility is especially important in metalworking because materials that crack or break under stress cannot be hammered, rolled, or drawn (drawing is a process that uses tensile forces to stretch metal).
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper has a higher ductility than alternate metal conductors with the exception of gold and silver.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Because of copper's high ductility, it is easy to draw down to diameters with very close tolerances.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Usually, the stronger a metal is, the less pliable it is.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] A unique combination of high strength and high ductility makes copper ideal for wiring systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] At junction boxes and at terminations, for example, copper can be bent, twisted, and pulled without stretching or breaking.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Creep is the gradual deformation of a material from constant expansions and contractions under varying load conditions.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This process has adverse effects on electrical systems: terminations can become loose, causing connections to heat up or create dangerous arcing.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper has excellent creep characteristics that minimizes loosening at connections.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] For other metal conductors that creep, extra maintenance is required to check terminals periodically and ensure that screws remain tightened to prevent arcing and overheating.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Corrosion is the unwanted breakdown and weakening of a material due to chemical reactions.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper generally resists corrosion from moisture, humidity, industrial pollution, and other atmospheric influences.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] However, any corrosion oxides, chlorides, and sulfides that do form on copper are somewhat conductive.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Under many application conditions copper is higher on the galvanic series than other common structural metals, meaning that copper wire is less likely to be corroded in wet conditions.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] However, any more anodic metals in contact with copper will be corroded since they will essentially be sacrificed to the copper.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Metals and other solid materials expand upon heating and contract upon cooling.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This is an undesirable occurrence in electrical systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper has a low coefficient of thermal expansion for an electrical conducting material.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Aluminium, an alternate common conductor, expands nearly one third more than copper under increasing temperatures.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This higher degree of expansion, along with aluminium's lower ductility, can cause electrical problems when bolted connections are improperly installed.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] By using proper hardware, such as spring pressure connections and cupped or split washers at the joint, it may be possible to create aluminium joints that compare in quality to copper joints.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Thermal conductivity is the ability of a material to conduct heat.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] In electrical systems, high thermal conductivity is important for dissipating waste heat, particularly at terminations and connections.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper has a 60% higher thermal conductivity rating than aluminium, so it is better able to reduce thermal hot spots in electrical wiring systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Soldering is a process whereby two or more metals are joined together by a heating process using a filler material that has a much lower melting point than the metal to be joined.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This is a desirable property in electrical systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper is readily soldered to make durable connections when necessary.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The strength, hardness, and flexibility of copper make it very easy to work with.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper wiring can be installed simply and easily with no special tools, washers, pigtails, or joint compounds.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Its flexibility makes it easy to join, while its hardness helps keep connections securely in place.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] It has good strength for pulling wire through tight places, including conduits.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] It can be bent or twisted easily without breaking.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] It can be stripped and terminated during installation or service with far less danger of nicks or breaks.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] And it can be connected without the use of special lugs and fittings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The combination of all of these factors makes it easy for electricians to install copper wire.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Solid wire consists of one strand of copper metal wire, bare or surrounded by an insulator.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Single-strand copper conductors are typically used as magnet wire in motors and transformers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] They are relatively rigid, do not bend easily, and are typically installed in permanent, infrequently handled, and low flex applications.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Stranded wire has a group of copper wires braided or twisted together.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Stranded wire is more flexible and easier to install than a large single-strand wire of the same cross section.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Stranding improves wire life in applications with vibration.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] A particular cross-section of a stranded conductor gives it essentially the same resistance characteristics as a single-strand conductor, but with added flexibility.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] A copper cable consists of two or more copper wires running side by side and bonded, twisted or braided together to form a single assembly.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Electrical cables may be made more flexible by stranding the wires.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper wires in a cable may be bare or they may be plated to reduce oxidation with a thin layer of another metal, most often tin but sometimes gold or silver.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Plating may lengthen wire life and makes soldering easier.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Twisted pair and coaxial cables are designed to inhibit electromagnetic interference, prevent radiation of signals, and to provide transmission lines with defined characteristics.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Shielded cables are encased in foil or wire mesh.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Electrolytic-tough pitch (ETP) copper, a high-purity copper that contains oxygen as an alloying agent, represents the bulk of electrical conductor applications because of its high electrical conductivity and improved annealability.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] ETP copper is used for power transmission, electric power distribution, and telecommunications.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Common applications include building wire, motor windings, electrical cables, and busbars.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Oxygen-free coppers are used to resist hydrogen embrittlement when extensive amounts of cold work is needed, and for applications requiring higher ductility (e.g., telecommunications cable).
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] When hydrogen embrittlement is a concern and low electrical resistivity is not required, phosphorus may be added to copper.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] For certain applications, copper alloy conductors are preferred instead of pure copper, especially when higher strengths or improved abrasion and corrosion resistance properties are required.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] However, relative to pure copper, the higher strength and corrosion resistance benefits that are offered by copper alloys are offset by their lower electrical conductivities.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Design engineers weigh the advantages and disadvantages of the various types of copper and copper alloy conductors when determining which type to specify for a specific electrical application.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] An example of a copper alloy conductor is cadmium copper wire, which is used for railroad electrification in North America.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] In Britain the BPO (later Post Office Telecommunications) used cadmium copper aerial lines with 1% cadmium for extra strength; for local lines 40 lb/mile (1.3 mm dia) and for toll lines 70 lb/mile (1.7 mm dia).
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Some of the major application markets for copper conductors are summarized below.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Electrical wiring distributes electric power inside residential, commercial, or industrial buildings, mobile homes, recreational vehicles, boats, and substations at voltages up to 600 V.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The thickness of the wire is based on electric current requirements in conjunction with safe operating temperatures.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Solid wire is used for smaller diameters; thicker diameters are stranded to provide flexibility.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper is commonly used for building wire because of its conductivity, strength, and reliability.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Over the life of a building wire system, copper can also be the most economical conductor.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper used in building wire has a conductivity rating of 100% IACS or better.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper building wire requires less insulation and can be installed in smaller conduits than when lower-conductivity conductors are used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Also, comparatively, more copper wire can fit in a given conduit than conductors with lower conductivities.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This greater *wire fill* is a special advantage when a system is rewired or expanded.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper building wire is compatible with brass and quality plated screws.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The wire provides connections that will not corrode or creep.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] It is not, however, compatible with aluminium wire or connectors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] If the two metals are joined, a galvanic reaction can occur.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Anodic corrosion during the reaction can disintegrate the aluminium.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This is why most appliance and electrical equipment manufacturers use copper lead wires for connections to building wiring systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Attempts to replace copper with aluminium in building wire were curtailed in most countries when it was found that aluminium connections gradually loosened due to their inherent slow creep, combined with the high resistivity and heat generation of aluminium oxidation at joints.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Spring-loaded contacts have largely alleviated this problem with aluminium conductors in building wire, but some building codes still forbid the use of aluminium.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] For branch-circuit sizes, virtually all basic wiring for lights, outlets and switches is made from copper.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The market for aluminium building wire today is mostly confined to larger gauge sizes used in supply circuits.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Electrical wiring codes give the allowable current rating for standard sizes of conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The current rating of a conductor varies depending on the size, allowable maximum temperature, and the operating environment of the conductor.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Conductors used in areas where cool air is free to circulate around the wires are generally permitted to carry more current than the small sized conductor encased in an underground conduit run with many similar conductors adjacent to it.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The practical temperature ratings of insulated copper conductors are mostly due to the limitations of the insulation material or of the temperature rating of the attached equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Twisted pair cabling is the most popular network cable and is often used in data networks for short and medium length connections (up to 100 meters or 328 feet).
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This is due to its relatively lower costs compared to optical fiber and coaxial cable.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Unshielded twisted pair (UTP) cables are the primary cable type for telephone usage.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] In the late 20th century, UTPs emerged as the most common cable in computer networking cables, especially as patch cables or temporary network connections.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] They are increasingly used in video applications, primarily in security cameras.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] UTP plenum cables that run above ceilings and inside walls use a solid copper core for each conductor, which enables the cable to hold its shape when bent.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Patch cables, which connect computers to wall plates, use stranded copper wire because they are expected to be flexed during their lifetimes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] UTPs are the best balanced-line wires available.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] However, they are the easiest to tap into.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] When interference and security are concerns, shielded cable or fiber-optic cable is often considered.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] UTP cables include: Category 3 cable, now the minimum requirement by the FCC (USA) for every telephone connection; Category 5e cable, 100-MHz enhanced pairs for running Gigabit Ethernet (1000BASE-T); and Category 6 cable, where each pair runs 250 MHz for improved 1000BASE-T performance.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] In copper twisted pair wire networks, copper cable certification is achieved through a thorough series of tests in accordance with Telecommunications Industry Association (TIA) or International Organization for Standardization (ISO) standards.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Coaxial cables were extensively used in mainframe computer systems and were the first type of major cable used for Local Area Networks (LAN).
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Common applications for coaxial cable today include computer network (Internet) and instrumentation data connections, video and CATV distribution, RF and microwave transmission, and feedlines connecting radio transmitters and receivers with their antennas.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] While coaxial cables can go longer distances and have better protection from EMI than twisted pairs, coaxial cables are harder to work with and more difficult to run from offices to the wiring closet.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] For these reasons, it is now generally being replaced with less expensive UTP cables or by fiber-optic cables for more capacity.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Today, many CATV companies still use coaxial cables into homes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] These cables, however, are increasingly connected to a fiber optic data communications system outside of the home.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Most building management systems use proprietary copper cabling, as do paging/audio speaker systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Security monitoring and entry systems still often depend on copper, although fiber cables are also used.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Most telephone lines can share voice and data simultaneously.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Pre-digital quad telephone wiring in homes is unable to handle communications needs for multiple phone lines, Internet service, video communications, data transmission, fax machines, and security services.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Crosstalk, static interference, inaudible signals, and interrupted service are common problems with outdated wiring.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Computers connected to old-fashioned communications wiring often experience poor Internet performance.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Structured cabling enables computers to communicate with each other error-free and at high speeds while resisting interference among various electrical sources, such as household appliances and external communications signals.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Networked computers are able to share high-speed Internet connections simultaneously.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Structured cabling can also connect computers with printers, scanners, telephones, fax machines, and even home security systems and home entertainment equipment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Quad-shielded RG-6 coaxial cable can carry a large number of TV channels at the same time.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] A star wiring pattern, where the wiring to each jack extends to a central distribution device, facilitates flexibility of services, problem identification, and better signal quality.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This pattern has advantages to daisy chain loops.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Installation tools, tips, and techniques for networked wiring systems using twisted pairs, coaxial cables, and connectors for each are available.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Structured cabling competes with wireless systems in homes.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Alternatively, wireless systems are a security risk as they can transmit sensitive information to unintended users over similar receiver devices.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Wireless systems are more susceptible to interference from other devices and systems, which can compromise performance.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Certain geographic areas and some buildings may be unsuitable for wireless installations, just as some buildings may present difficulties installing wires.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Electric power distribution is the final stage in the delivery of electricity for an end use.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] A power distribution system carries electricity from the transmission system to consumers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Power cables are used for the transmission and distribution of electric power, either outdoors or inside buildings.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Details on the various types of power cables are available.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper is the preferred conductor material for underground transmission lines operating at high and extra-high voltages to 400 kV.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The predominance of copper underground systems stems from its higher volumetric electrical and thermal conductivities compared to other conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] These beneficial properties for copper conductors conserve space, minimize power loss, and maintain lower cable temperatures.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper continues to dominate low-voltage lines in mines and underwater applications, as well as in electric railroads, hoists, and other outdoor services.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Aluminium, either alone or reinforced with steel, is the preferred conductor for overhead transmission lines due to its lighter weight and lower cost.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Appliance conductors for domestic applications and instruments are manufactured from bunch-stranded soft wire, which may be tinned for soldering or phase identification.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Depending upon loads, insulation can be PVC, neoprene, ethylene propylene, polypropylene filler, or cotton.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Automotive conductors require insulation that is resistant to elevated temperatures, petroleum products, humidity, fire, and chemicals.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] PVC, neoprene, and polyethylene are the most common insulators.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Potentials range from 12 V for electrical systems to between 300 V - 15,000 V for instruments, lighting, and ignition systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Magnet wire or winding wire is used in windings of electric motors, transformers, inductors, generators, headphones, loudspeaker coils, hard drive head positioners, electromagnets, and other devices.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Most often, magnetic wire is composed of fully annealed, electrolytically refined copper to allow closer winding when making electromagnetic coils.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The wire is coated with a range of polymeric insulations, including varnish, rather than the thicker plastic or other types of insulation commonly used on electrical wire.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] High-purity oxygen-free copper grades are used for high-temperature applications in reducing atmospheres or in motors or generators cooled by hydrogen gas.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] A copper splice closure is defined as an enclosure, and the associated hardware, that is intended to restore the mechanical and environmental integrity of one or more copper cables entering the enclosure and providing some internal function for splicing, termination, or interconnection.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] As stated in Telcordia industry requirements document GR-3151, there are two principal configurations for closures: butt closures and in-line closures.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Butt closures permit cables to enter the closure from one end only.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This design may also be referred to as a dome closure.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] These closures can be used in a variety of applications, including branch splicing.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] In-line closures provide for the entry of cables at both ends of the closure.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] They can be used in a variety of applications, including branch splicing and cable access.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] In-line closures can also be used in a butt configuration by restricting cable access to one end of the closure.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] A copper splice closure is defined by the functional design characteristics and, for the most part, is independent of specific deployment environments or applications.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] ESCs provide all of the features and functions expected of a typical splice closure in an enclosure that prevents the intrusion of liquid and vapor into the closure interior.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] This is accomplished through the use of an environmental sealing system such as rubber gaskets or hot-melt adhesives.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Some ESCs use pressurized air to help keep moisture out of the closure.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] FBCs provide all of the features and functions expected of a typical splice closure that prevents the intrusion of wind-driven rain, dust, and insects.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Such a closure, however, permits the free exchange of air with the outside environment.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Therefore, it is possible that condensation will form inside the closure.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] It is thus necessary to provide adequate drainage to prevent the accumulation of water inside the closure.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Copper is expected to continue to be the predominant material in most electrical wire applications, especially where space considerations are important.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The automotive industry for decades has considered the use of smaller-diameter wires in certain applications.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Some manufacturers are beginning to use copper alloys such as copper-magnesium (CuMg), which has less conductivity but more strength than pure copper.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Due to the need to increase the transmission of high-speed voice and data signals, the surface quality of copper wire is expected to continue to improve.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Demands for better drawability and movement towards *zero* defects in copper conductors are expected to continue.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] A minimum mechanical strength requirement for magnet wire may evolve in order to improve formability and prevent excessive stretching of wire during high-speed coiling operations.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] It does not seem likely that standards for copper wire purity will increase beyond the current minimum value of 101% IACS.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Although 6-nines copper (99.9999% pure) has been produced in small quantities, it is extremely expensive and probably unnecessary for most commercial applications such as magnet, telecommunications, and building wire.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] The electrical conductivity of 6-nines copper and 4-nines copper (99.99% pure) is nearly the same at ambient temperature, although the higher-purity copper has a higher conductivity at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Therefore, for non-cryogenic temperatures, 4-nines copper will probably remain the dominant material for most commercial wire applications.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] As of 2024 the Chilean Copper Commission expected copper to face increased competition from aluminium in high, medium and low voltage transmission lines but not in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] During the 2000s commodities boom, copper prices increased worldwide, increasing the incentive for criminals to steal copper from power supply and communications cables.
[src:ground-and-neutral/copper-wire-and-cable] Iranian Minister of ICT has replaced copper with fiber optic because of theft.
[src:ground-and-neutral/delta-wye-transformer] A **delta–wye transformer** (**Δ–Y transformer**) is a type of three-phase electric power transformer design that employs delta-connected windings on its primary and wye/star connected windings on its secondary.
[src:ground-and-neutral/delta-wye-transformer] A neutral wire can be provided on wye output side.
[src:ground-and-neutral/delta-wye-transformer] It can be a single three-phase transformer, or built from three independent single-phase units.
[src:ground-and-neutral/delta-wye-transformer] An equivalent term is **delta–star transformer**.
[src:ground-and-neutral/delta-wye-transformer] Delta–wye transformers are common in commercial, industrial, and high-density residential locations, to supply three-phase distribution systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/delta-wye-transformer] The delta winding allows third-harmonic currents to circulate within the transformer, and prevents third-harmonic currents from flowing in the supply line.
[src:ground-and-neutral/delta-wye-transformer] Delta–wye transformers introduce a 30, 150, 210, or 330 degree phase shift.
[src:ground-and-neutral/delta-wye-transformer] Thus they cannot be paralleled with wye–wye (or delta–delta) transformers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/delta-wye-transformer] However, they can be paralleled with identical configurations and some different configurations of other delta–wye (or wye–delta with some attention) transformers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In electrical engineering, **ground** (or **earth**) and **neutral** are circuit conductors used in alternating current (AC) electrical systems.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] The neutral conductor carries alternating current (in tandem with one or more *phase line* conductors) during normal operation of the circuit.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In such case the intention is for the fault current to be large enough to trigger a circuit protective device that will either de-energize the circuit (via a fuse or circuit breaker) or provide a warning.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] To limit the effects of leakage current from higher-voltage systems, the neutral conductor is often connected to earth ground at the point of supply.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Significant voltage unintentionally appearing on exposed conductive parts of an electrical installation can present danger, so the installation of ground and neutral conductors is carefully regulated in electrical safety standards.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Under certain strict conditions the same conductor may be used for providing both ground and neutral functions together.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] A **ground** or **earth** conductor, or **CPC (circuit protective conductor)**, in an AC power system is a conductor that provides a low-impedance path to the Earth to prevent hazardous voltages from appearing on equipment (high voltage spikes).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] The terms *ground* and *earth* are used synonymously in this section; *ground* is more common in North American English, and *earth* or the more technical term *CPC* is more common in British English.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Under normal conditions, a ground conductor does not carry current.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Ground conductors are essential for automatically cutting power in the event of ground faults.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] International Electrotechnical Commission standard IEC 60364 codifies methods of installing neutral and ground conductors in a building.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] These earthing systems arrangements are designated with letter symbols.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In North American and European practice, suitably designed mains-powered portable equipment is permitted to have merely two conductors in their attachment plug (line and neutral), foregoing use of the available earth connection.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Such appliances are known in the UK as *Class-II* or *double-insulated*.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] A **neutral** conductor, in combination with one or more **phase line** conductors, normally completes a circuit between the source and load.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In a polyphase (usually three-phase) AC system however, the neutral conductor may carry very little current if the phases are balanced and in some cases may thus not be provided.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Neutral wires are typically "bonded" to Earth (ground) at either the electrical service entrance, or at transformers within the system.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] An exception to this is found in the IT earthing arrangement.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] For electrical installations with split-phase (three-wire single-phase) service, the neutral point of the system is at the center-tap on the secondary side of the service transformer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] For larger electrical installations, such as those with polyphase service, the neutral point is usually at the common connection on the secondary side of delta/wye connected transformers.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Other arrangements of polyphase transformers may result in no neutral point, and no neutral conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Stray voltages created in grounding (earthing) conductors by currents flowing in the supply utility neutral conductors can be troublesome.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] For example, special measures may be required in barns used for milking dairy cattle.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Very small voltages, not usually perceptible to humans, may cause low milk yield, or even mastitis (inflammation of the udder).
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] So-called "tingle voltage filters" may be required in the electrical distribution system for a milking parlour.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Connecting the neutral to the equipment case (if permitted by relevant regulations) provides some protection against faults, but may produce a dangerous voltage on the case if the neutral connection is broken.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Combined neutral and ground conductors are commonly used in electricity supply companies' wiring and occasionally for fixed wiring in buildings and for some specialist applications where there is little alternative, such as railways and trams.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In the United States, the cases of some kitchen stoves (ranges, ovens), cook tops, clothes dryers and other specifically *listed* appliances were grounded through their neutral wires as a measure to conserve copper from copper cables during World War II.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] This practice was removed from the NEC in the 1996 edition, but existing installations (called "old work") may still allow this to remain in place.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Using the neutral conductor for grounding the equipment enclosure was considered safe since the devices were permanently wired to the supply and so the neutral was unlikely to be broken without also breaking both supply conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] A **shared neutral** is a connection in which a plurality of circuits use the same neutral connection.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] This is also known as a **common neutral**, and the circuits and neutral together are sometimes referred to as an **Edison circuit**.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In a three-phase circuit, a neutral is shared between all three phases.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Commonly the system neutral is connected to the star point on the feeding transformer.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] This is the reason that the secondary side of most three-phase distribution transformers is wye- or star-wound.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] A system could be made entirely ungrounded.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In this case a fault between one phase and ground would not cause any significant current.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Commonly the neutral is grounded (earthed) through a bond between the neutral bar and the earth bar.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] It is common on larger systems to monitor any current flowing through the neutral-to-earth link and use this as the basis for neutral fault protection.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In a three-phase linear circuit with three identical resistive or reactive loads, the neutral carries no current.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] The neutral carries current if the loads on each phase are not identical.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In some jurisdictions, the neutral is allowed to be reduced in size if no unbalanced current flow is expected.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] If the neutral is smaller than the phase conductors, it can be overloaded if a large unbalanced load occurs.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] The current drawn by non-linear loads, such as fluorescent & HID lighting and electronic equipment containing switching power supplies, often contains harmonics.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Triplen harmonic currents (odd multiples of the third harmonic) are additive, resulting in more current in the shared neutral conductor than in any of the phase conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] In the absolute worst case, the current in the shared neutral conductor can be triple that in each phase conductor.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] Some jurisdictions prohibit the use of shared neutral conductors when feeding single-phase loads from a three-phase source; others require that the neutral conductor be substantially larger than the phase conductors.
[src:ground-and-neutral/ground-and-neutral] It is good practice to use four-pole circuit breakers (as opposed to the standard three-pole) where the fourth pole is the neutral phase, and is hence protected against overcurrent on the neutral conductor.
